  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_263005396" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/263005396" />
    <a title="Punk" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/116652-punk"><img alt="Punk" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1181025939p2/116652.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/263005396?book_show_action=true">Jan 16, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Punk" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Punk" href="/user/show/116652-punk">Punk</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9780739497494" href="/book/show/25508023-the-gift-of-fear">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/116652-punk?shelf=non-fiction">non-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer263005396" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer402000455543801904">The premise of this book is that if you trust your intuition and learn to recognize certain signs that often precede violence, you can live free of fear because you&apos;ll have the tools to identify a threat should one occur and so the rest of the time you can just go ahead and relax.<br/><br/>Are you relaxed yet?<br/><br/>The problem is that this book came out in 1997 and hasn&apos;t been revised or updated in the almost twenty years since it was published. In 1997, Mark Zuckerberg was thirteen, less than four percent of t</span>
  <span id="freeText402000455543801904" style="display:none">The premise of this book is that if you trust your intuition and learn to recognize certain signs that often precede violence, you can live free of fear because you'll have the tools to identify a threat should one occur and so the rest of the time you can just go ahead and relax.<br /><br />Are you relaxed yet?<br /><br />The problem is that this book came out in 1997 and hasn't been revised or updated in the almost twenty years since it was published. In 1997, Mark Zuckerberg was thirteen, less than four percent of the world owned a cell phone, and you didn't have to take your shoes off before you got on an airplane. A lot has changed in the intervening years, and at times this book sounds completely out of touch.<br /><br />Other times, it sounds a little too proud of itself. I preferred when de Becker gave real world examples and used them to teach instead of making up examples and speaking theoretically. The former is easy to read; the latter edged into italicized theatrics. There's some good advice under the bombast, but even as he complains about local news sensationalizing violence, parts of his book—like the chapters on stalkers and assassins—make him guilty of the same thing. Knowing how many assassins carry around a copy of <i>The Catcher in the Rye</i> isn't going to keep me safe; that's just de Becker showing off.<br /><br />So this book is good and bad, and I took what I could from it. I like that he says we have to teach people that 'No' is a complete sentence. That we have to encourage women to say no, and teach men to hear it. But the rest is him mansplaining domestic violence and <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/user_status/show/79947295" rel="nofollow noopener">blaming the victims</a>, and, without exception, de Becker speaks of men as the abusers and women as the victims. He makes no attempt to use gender-neutral language, or acknowledge that women can be abusers or that there are relationships out there that aren't heterosexual. This is written from a straight white man's perspective, and it shows. There's not one word about hate crimes, violence against people of color, or how dangerous it is just to walk around being queer or <a href="http://tdor.info/" rel="nofollow noopener">trans</a>.<br /><br />Two stars. A limited, and dated, take on fear and violence. The first few chapters and the section on how to spot when <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Gift_of_Fear#PINS_(Pre-Incident_Indicators)" rel="nofollow noopener">someone is using charm as a way of gaining trust for malicious reasons</a> were potentially useful, but the author's attitude toward domestic abuse was offensive and gendered, and the last third of the book had little to do with everyday life. <br /><br />Contains discussion of interpersonal violence, abuse, rape, child harm, self-harm, and animal harm.</span>
  <a data-text-id="402000455543801904" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

