<div id="review_2593213254" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2593213254" />
    <a title="B" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2957848-b"><img alt="B" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1359603669p2/2957848.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2593213254?book_show_action=true">Jan 18, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="B" class="user" itemprop="url" name="B" href="/user/show/2957848-b">B</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="did not like it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">did not like it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2593213254" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7132228137897335911">Yoooooooooo this book sucks!<br/><br/>Gavin de Becker spent his professional career attempting to protect women from violence. So how in the hell did he become so damn sexist?!<br/><br/>I went into this book looking for academic discourse on violence inflicted on people by people. I wanted to read about how to see and react warning signs, how to de-escalate potentially dangerous situations, and perhaps read up on some of the psychology behind violence.<br/><br/>That is so not what this book is about.<br/><br/>This book is about statin</span>
  <span id="freeText7132228137897335911" style="display:none">Yoooooooooo this book sucks!<br /><br />Gavin de Becker spent his professional career attempting to protect women from violence. So how in the hell did he become so damn sexist?!<br /><br />I went into this book looking for academic discourse on violence inflicted on people by people. I wanted to read about how to see and react warning signs, how to de-escalate potentially dangerous situations, and perhaps read up on some of the psychology behind violence.<br /><br />That is so not what this book is about.<br /><br />This book is about stating the obvious with no actual practical applications, while managing to tell women they're stupid in one overly long, overly graphic narrative. <br /><br />Let's break down some of the more egregious passages, shall we?<br /><br /><i>"Cynthia is a substitute schoolteacher, a funny, beautiful woman totally unlike the dull and much-harassed substitutes most of us recall from our school years."</i><br />Hi. You are objectifying this woman for no reason. Nice.<br /><br /><i>"I encourage women to ask other women for help when they need it, and it’s likewise safer to accept an offer from a woman than from a man. (Unfortunately, women rarely make such offers to other women, and I wish more would.)"</i><br />What the actual fuck. How do you have any sort of reliable statistic stating that women <b>rarely</b> offer to help other women. You don't offer any evidence, so we'll have to assume you're a big, fat liar who thinks women are useless. It is insulting. It is disgusting. Shame on you, sir.<br /><br />When discussing how a man woke up in the middle of the night to a noise, went downstairs to investigate, didn't find anything, and ultimately woke up a second time to a man standing over him with a gun:<br /><i>"Had he responded to his fear with respect, he would have found the intruder before the intruder found his gun. If he had said, in effect, 'Since I feel fear, I know there is some reason, so what is it?'"</i><br />So... wait... you're telling me every time I hear a noise in my house it's a murderer and I should stay up all night waiting for the attack? What in the hell is de Becker trying to get at with this passage (we don't know, because he never elaborates on the point of this or HOW one respects fear without being a slave to it). He spends a decent chunk of the book telling women that they are worried about the possibility of violence, which manifests fear for no reason, and we all need to chill the fuck out. But for some reason a random noise in the night (which happens to all of us at some point) is cause to ASSUME there is a murderer in the house?! How is that logic?! I'm thinking it was because it was a MAN who heard the noise, and that MEN should trust their fear while WOMEN are afraid of possibility rather than actuality. Because what else am I supposed to take away from this? SERIOUSLY. TELL ME.<br /><br />In general, de Becker tells us that the warning signs of violence are "obvious," but that is patently untrue. Each person is unique, and each person reacts to levels of engagement/non-engagement differently. To claim there is one universal way to handle people is naive and, quite frankly, dangerous. He also goes on to claim that the police are relatively useless in many cases... so what does knowing these warning signs actually do for us? Who knows - certainly not de Becker. <br /><br />And finally:<br /><br /><i>"I believe that the first time a woman is hit, she is a victim and the second time, she is a volunteer"</i><br />Fuck you.</span>
  <a data-text-id="7132228137897335911" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


