    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2816586308" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2816586308" />
    <a title="Audrey" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5630113-audrey"><img alt="Audrey" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1572483937p2/5630113.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2816586308?book_show_action=true">May 31, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Audrey" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Audrey" href="/user/show/5630113-audrey">Audrey</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780440508830" href="/book/show/1223772.The_Gift_of_Fear">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5630113-audrey?shelf=2019-books">2019-books</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5630113-audrey?shelf=non-fiction">non-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2816586308" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14695729267230401059">First of all, this book is woefully outdated. Since it was written, nearly everyone has bought a cell phone, employers screen applicants, security checkpoints have sprung up everywhere, and no one uses the term “battered women” anymore. We went through a whole “No means no!” campaign. We also recognize today that men can be abused by women, which the author generally dismisses as preposterous.<br/><br/>Second of all, the statistics he uses are so wrong, they’re just made up. They weren’t true at time of p</span>
  <span id="freeText14695729267230401059" style="display:none">First of all, this book is woefully outdated. Since it was written, nearly everyone has bought a cell phone, employers screen applicants, security checkpoints have sprung up everywhere, and no one uses the term “battered women” anymore. We went through a whole “No means no!” campaign. We also recognize today that men can be abused by women, which the author generally dismisses as preposterous.<br><br>Second of all, the statistics he uses are so wrong, they’re just made up. They weren’t true at time of publication either. Misleading data is sensationalist at best and dangerous at work. There are ZERO citations in this book. He dismisses the idea that women can capably use guns for self-defense. (See <a href="https://www.dailysignal.com/2019/05/10/the-second-amendment-saved-these-gun-owners-lives-in-april/?utm_source=TDS_Email&amp;utm_medium=email&amp;utm_campaign=MorningBell&amp;mkt_tok=eyJpIjoiTURVMFlXUXpObU14Tm1RMCIsInQiOiJwVFY2V2Y1d2huUFpiQU9iODMwMHNxQjZoY3g5bXhkUlJ4Y1ZrN3l1UlpIZ3NEamgzN3JLQUdXTXNPR1BEZ01TSlRHMVQ2SGtsTDRzZFFld0I1cFBXbHNcL0NnUFQrUkdSeUJnVlRhVllmc2h3U1hzYlVMVlMwdEhNa1JUd2FsaVoifQ%3D%3D" rel="nofollow noopener"> here</a> for a list of just a few cases of people defending themselves just last month.)<br><br>Much of the book goes over attacks by total strangers, which is quite rare in real life. Then the author brags about how he protected this secret famous client and that one. (He’s very proud of himself, though he never provides any credentials.) He sensationalizes violence at times and then at the end criticizes news media for doing the same. I found the anecdotes the most interesting, though there were a lot fewer than I was expecting or hoping for.<br><br>The author throws out all these acronyms he made up as part of his brand. I’m not wasting energy memorizing a bunch of 90s corporate buzzwords that feel straight out of a Dilbert cartoon. It’s like a really long infomercial.<br><br><img src="https://images.gr-assets.com/hostedimages/1559360851ra/27600260.gif" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br>The books takes a lot of pages to say very little. It started to get quite redundant. Let me save you the time by summing up:<br><br><img src="https://images.gr-assets.com/hostedimages/1473140683ra/20414446.gif" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br>1) Trust your gut instincts.<br>2) Get rid of unwanted attention (including stalkers) by ignoring it. Don’t worry about hurting someone’s feelings in rejecting them.<br>3) If you are dating someone who displays even a hint of violent behavior, run away.<br><br>Read the first chapter and the last chapter and skim the appendices.<br><br><a href="https://audreytheeditor.blogspot.com/" rel="nofollow noopener"> Book Blog</a></span>
  <a data-text-id="14695729267230401059" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


